  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async CLI (fetch → filter → dedupe/store → notify), not a web app — there's **no React/frontend code** in the repo, so that category doesn't apply here. I found real equivalents of the other four categories, with the store.py N+1 and the filters.py regex recompilation being the two worth fixing.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nOne `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every scan:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\",\n                          (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        ...\n```\n\nWith boards like Microsoft/Amazon running into thousands of listings per scan, this is thousands of round-trips where one would do. Fix — load the existing key→hash map in a single query, then do the diff purely in memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n    new, changed = [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis trades one full-table read for N indexed point-selects — a clear win unless `jobs` grows to a size where holding key/hash pairs in memory becomes a concern (it won't, at these row counts: two short strings × tens of thousands of rows is negligible).\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile(include)` / `_compile(exclude)` internally — so the same include/exclude keyword list gets turned into `re.Pattern` objects **once per job**, not once per run:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFix — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None,\n          locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\nSame regex-compile cost today is `O(jobs × keywords)`; this makes it `O(keywords)`.\n\n### 3. Caching opportunities\n\n- **HTTP conditional requests**: fetchers like `fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_amazon`/`fetch_google` do a full paginated re-fetch of boards with thousands of listings on every run, with no ETag/If-Modified-Since. Most of these ATS APIs don't support conditional GET, but for the ones that return a `Last-Modified`/`ETag` (worth checking Greenhouse/Lever, which are simple GETs via `_simple`), caching the response and short-circuiting on a 304 would cut both latency and the target sites' load — good citizenship for a scraper hitting the same boards every 12h (per the scheduled-run commit).\n- **`Job.content_hash` / `Job.posted_dt`** (`models.py:60-69`) are `@property`, recomputed via `hashlib.sha256` / `parse_posted_at` on every access. In `store.diff`, a changed job triggers `job.content_hash` (compare) then `job.to_row()` → `self.content_hash` again (insert/update) — hashing the same string twice. Since `Job` is a frozen-shape dataclass for the duration of a run, memoizing wouldn't need invalidation logic — e.g. compute once in `to_row()` and reuse:\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = (h := self.content_hash)\n    return d\n```\nand have `diff()` reuse `job.to_row()`'s hash instead of calling `job.content_hash` separately. Minor (one sha256 over a short string), not worth doing unless you're already touching this code.\n\n### 4. Memory / resource concerns (no true \"leaks\" — this is a short-lived CLI process, not a long-running server)\n\n- **`store.py`**: the `jobs` table only ever grows — `diff()` inserts/updates but nothing ever deletes stale postings that disappeared from a board. Not a memory leak, but an unbounded-growth issue for `jobs.db` (already 500KB and climbing per commit history). If old, no-longer-listed jobs aren't useful to you, consider a periodic prune (e.g. `DELETE FROM jobs WHERE last_seen < ?` past some retention window) or at least document that it's append-only by design.\n- **`notify.py:105-110`**: `dispatch()` runs Slack/webhook/email/SMS notifiers **sequentially and synchronously** (blocking `httpx.post` calls) inside what is otherwise an async pipeline. Each failed/slow notifier (e.g. SMTP timeout) blocks the others. Since this only fires once per run with ≤5 notifiers, it's low-impact, but if you ever add more notifiers or one starts flaking, wrapping them in `asyncio.gather` (or at least a thread pool) would stop one slow channel from delaying the rest.\n\n### 5. What's already good (don't touch)\n\n- `Store.next_seq` correctly uses `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` to serialize concurrent pipeline workers — deliberate, matches the note in memory about [[jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions]].\n- `fetch_all` bounds concurrency with a semaphore and isolates failures per-source — no unbounded fan-out.\n- Pagination loops (`fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_apple`, etc.) use `seen: set[str]` to stop on the first page with nothing new, capped by `max_pages` — bounded, not leaking.\n\n**Priority order**: fix #1 (store N+1) and #2 (filters regex) first — both are real, cheap, mechanical fixes. #3/#4 are optional depending on how large your boards/db get.\n",
